articles.title: JPMorgan CEO Jamie Dimon turned up to open D.C.'s newest Chase Bank branch. Here's why.
articles.summary: JPMorgan Chase CEO Jamie Dimon participated in the opening of a new Chase Bank branch at Skyland Town Center in D.C.'s Ward 7, joined by D.C. Mayor Muriel Bowser. The event marked the culmination of a long-awaited project.

articles.title: JPMorgan Chase acquires college financial planning platform Frank
articles.summary: JPMorgan Chase & Co (JPM.N) announced the acquisition of Frank, a college financial planning platform serving over 5 million students in the United States. This deal marks the latest in a series of acquisitions by the largest U.S. bank aimed at deepening its ties with students. The financial terms of the acquisition were not disclosed, and Frank's founder and CEO, Charlie Javice, will continue to lead the firm within JPMorgan Chase.

articles.title: JPMorgan Chase is buying college financial aid platform Frank to deepen ties with students
articles.summary: JPMorgan Chase has acquired Frank, a college financial aid platform, to strengthen its relationships with students and their parents, as well as to expand its customer base. Frank, which has served over 5 million students, helps with financial aid applications, online courses, and scholarships. This acquisition is part of JPMorgan's broader strategy to aggressively acquire fintech players and generate loyalty with specific demographic cohorts.

articles.title: Florida miner's lawsuit accuses JPMorgan of manipulating silver prices
articles.summary: A Florida-based silver miner, Hidalgo Mining Corp, has filed a lawsuit against JPMorgan, alleging the bank manipulated the silver market, causing prices to drop so low that its Mexican mine had to close. The complaint, filed in the U.S. District Court for the Southern District of Florida, uses information from a U.S. regulatory investigation into JPMorgan's spoofing activities between 2008 and 2016. JPMorgan has previously paid over $920 million to settle this investigation and $15.7 million to settle a class-action lawsuit related to the manipulation.

articles.title: EXCLUSIVE JPMorgan faces oil bribery probe in Brazil
articles.summary: JPMorgan Chase & Co. is under investigation by Brazilian authorities for its alleged involvement in a bribery and money laundering scheme related to state-run oil company Petrobras dating back to 2011. The probe focuses on purchases of Petrobras fuel oil and seeks to determine if bribe payments were routed to Petrobras employees to secure artificially low prices. This investigation is part of a larger crackdown on corruption within the commodity trading industry in Brazil.

articles.title: JPMorgan Chase adopts Thought Machine's Vault cloud system for core retail banking operations
articles.summary: JPMorgan Chase is moving its core retail banking system to Thought Machine's cloud-based Vault platform to meet changing customer demands, improve scalability, and support embedded banking. This adoption allows JPMorgan to run all retail banking products on a single, cloud-native platform. The move is part of JPMorgan's increased aggression in acquisitions, following recent purchases of college planning platform Frank and restaurant review service The Infatuation.

articles.title: AES-Siemens joint venture Fluence joins raft of storage firms moving to go public
articles.summary: Energy storage company Fluence, a joint venture between Siemens and AES, has filed for an initial public offering (IPO) to be listed on Nasdaq under "FLNC". This move follows increased investor interest in battery startups and marks Fluence's significant growth since its 2018 launch, including its AI platform and a recent $125 million investment from Qatar's sovereign wealth fund. The company joins several other storage firms that have recently gone public, capitalizing on the rising demand for energy storage solutions.

articles.title: Motley Fool to convert its mutual funds into ETFs
articles.summary: Motley Fool Asset Management plans to convert two mutual funds, totaling over $1 billion in assets, into ETFs by the end of the year. This move follows a growing trend in the industry, with firms like Dimensional Fund Advisors and JPMorgan Asset Management also making significant conversions. Analysts attribute this shift to the tax advantages, lower costs, and increasing investor preference for ETFs over traditional mutual funds.

articles.title: Nueva simplificación de Grupo Aval en Centroamérica
articles.summary: Grupo Aval is simplifying its structure in Central America by spinning off 75% of Leasing Bogotá S.A. Panamá (LBP), a subsidiary of Banco de Bogotá. This move will require a capital increase and is aimed at making decision-making more efficient and generating shareholder value. LBP plans to list its shares on the Colombian Stock Exchange, pending regulatory approvals.

articles.title: Why Intuit Paid $500 Million for Naming Rights at Clippers Arena
articles.summary: Intuit paid $500 million for the naming rights to the Los Angeles Clippers' new 18,000-seat arena, the Intuit Dome, for 23 years. This deal is part of a broader partnership focusing on fan experience, technology, and community involvement in Inglewood. The agreement aims to boost Intuit's public profile and contribute to the economic development and job creation in the area.

articles.title: Confluent Stock, MongoDB, Sprout Social Among 9 New Stocks On IBD Watchlists
articles.summary: Investor's Business Daily (IBD) has updated its stock watchlists, adding new companies like Confluent, MongoDB, and Sprout Social, while removing others that show weakness. These lists, including the IBD 50, Sector Leaders, and IBD Big Cap 20, are regularly revised to reflect current market conditions and identify potential investment opportunities. The changes help investors stay informed about leading stocks and those nearing buy points.

articles.title: FreshWorks lists; valued at $13 billion
articles.summary: Freshworks debuted on Nasdaq, with its shares surging 28% above the IPO price to reach a market value of $13 billion. This makes Freshworks the first India-born software-as-a-service firm to trade on a US exchange, setting a new valuation benchmark for Indian startups. The successful listing and strong investor interest highlight a new era for similar Indian companies looking to go public in the US.

articles.title: Brilliant Earth Announces Pricing of Initial Public Offering
articles.summary: Brilliant Earth Group, Inc. has announced the pricing of its initial public offering of 8,333,333 shares of Class A common stock at $12.00 per share. The shares are expected to begin trading on the Nasdaq Global Select Market under the ticker symbol "BRLT" on September 23, 2021, with the offering closing on September 27, 2021. J.P. Morgan, Credit Suisse, Jefferies, and Cowen are acting as lead book-running managers for the offering, which also includes an option for underwriters to purchase an additional 1,249,999 shares.

articles.title: Los Angeles Daily News - Definitive Healthcare Announces Closing of Public Offering
articles.summary: Definitive Healthcare Corp. announced the closing of its initial public offering of 17,888,888 shares of its Class A common stock, including the full exercise of the underwriters' option. The offering was priced at $27.00 per share, generating approximately $483 million in gross proceeds before expenses. The company's Class A common stock began trading on Nasdaq under the ticker symbol "DH" on September 15, 2021.

articles.title: As Interest Rates Rise, Leverage Financial Sector Strength
articles.summary: The article discusses investment opportunities within the financial sector as the Federal Reserve signals rising interest rates in 2022. It highlights how rising rates benefit banks and the financial sector, suggesting the Direxion Daily Financial Bull 3X ETF (FAS) for leveraged plays. Despite potential dampening effects on mortgage demand, a hot housing sector and rising home prices could lead to larger loan amounts, balancing out this impact.

articles.title: Advent-owned hair-care company Olaplex targets over $10 bln valuation in U.S. IPO
articles.summary: Olaplex Holdings Inc, a hair-care products maker owned by Advent International, is seeking a valuation of up to $10.4 billion in its U.S. initial public offering. The company plans to offer 67 million shares priced between $14 and $16 each, aiming to raise $1.07 billion. Olaplex will list its shares on the Nasdaq under the symbol "OLPX" with Goldman Sachs, J.P. Morgan, Morgan Stanley, and Barclays as lead underwriters.

articles.title: Rivian details $1 billion loss, Amazon deal in IPO filing
articles.summary: Rivian Automotive Inc., an electric pickup maker backed by Amazon.com Inc., disclosed a net loss of almost $1 billion in the first half of the year in its initial public offering paperwork. The company is seeking to be valued at about $80 billion and has significant backing from investors like Amazon and Ford Motor Co., alongside strong pre-order interest for its vehicles. The filing also detailed its exclusive four-year deal with Amazon for delivery vehicles, although Amazon isn't bound by minimum purchase requirements.

articles.title: A new ETF will let investors buy into risky debt some call 'ground zero' for the next financial crisis
articles.summary: Janus Henderson has filed for a new ETF that will allow investors to buy into collateralized loan obligations (CLOs), specifically those with lower, riskier credit ratings (B-BBB+). While some analysts warn against opening such risky assets to retail investors, citing potential liquidity issues if the market falters, these lower-rated CLOs can offer higher yields compared to other investment options like top-rated CLOs or Treasury bills. The move brings a complex and potentially lucrative, yet highly speculative, asset class to a broader investor base.

articles.title: Robo Advisors An Evolving Field
articles.summary: Robo advisors are undergoing significant evolution to meet complex customer needs, particularly from younger investors. The industry is exploring hybrid models combining automation with human guidance, alongside fully automated services, to provide a broader range of financial advice and planning options. This shift aims to cater to both those seeking independent tools and those who eventually desire a more personalized, high-touch service.

articles.title: Fintech and traditional banks: competition or… symbiosis?
articles.summary: This article examines the relationship between fintechs and traditional banks in the UK, questioning if it's competition or symbiosis. It analyzes customer usage of digital-only services versus traditional banking platforms, highlighting that while fintechs are growing, they often complement rather than replace traditional banks, especially among younger demographics. The author suggests that traditional banks still hold a massive audience and can leverage cross-selling strategies, indicating a more complex interaction than simple competition.

articles.title: Clearwater Analytics Announces Pricing of Initial Public Offering
articles.summary: Clearwater Analytics announced the pricing of its initial public offering of 30,000,000 shares of Class A common stock at $18.00 per share, with an option for underwriters to purchase an additional 4,500,000 shares. The shares are expected to begin trading on the New York Stock Exchange under the symbol "CWAN" on September 24, 2021, and the offering is set to close on September 28, 2021. Goldman Sachs & Co. LLC, J.P. Morgan Securities LLC, and Morgan Stanley & Co. LLC are serving as lead bookrunners for the offering.

articles.title: Keeping the faith – Diana van Maasdijk
articles.summary: Diana van Maasdijk, CEO of Equileap, discusses the company's journey from skepticism to a crucial data provider for gender equality in the workplace. Equileap provides granular data and partners with Nasdaq ESG Hub, emphasizing the increasing investor focus on the "social" aspect of ESG. The article details Equileap's data collection methods, the impact of its Gender Equality Scorecard, and the growing evidence linking gender equality to improved financial performance.

articles.title: Leak reveals how Swiss wealth consultants shield global cast of suspects
articles.summary: The Pandora Papers leak exposes how Swiss wealth consultants, notably Fidinam Group, exploit regulatory gaps to help the rich and powerful hide money and evade taxes. The documents detail Fidinam's involvement in a $600 million embezzlement scheme and connections to clients under criminal investigation, showcasing the opaque nature of Switzerland's advisory industry. The article highlights the failure of Swiss lawmakers to implement stricter anti-money laundering rules for advisers, despite evidence from previous leaks.
articles.source: International Consortium of Investigative Journalists - ICIJ

articles.title: Citizens Financial Group Appoints Sarah Lindstrom as Head of Business Banking
articles.summary: Citizens Financial Group announced the appointment of Sarah Lindstrom as Head of Business Banking, effective October 4. Lindstrom, who joined Citizens in 2017, will be responsible for growing the business banking portfolio and developing the team. Her leadership is expected to benefit customers and the Business Banking team as the company continues to expand this important segment.

articles.title: ON THE MOVE: Northern Trust Names Manioudakis CIO; Goldman Sachs Promotes Coleman to CFO
articles.summary: Northern Trust Asset Management has appointed Angelo Manioudakis as its new Chief Investment Officer, bringing his extensive experience from other global financial firms. Concurrently, Goldman Sachs has promoted Denis P. Coleman III to Chief Financial Officer, succeeding Stephen M. Scherr who is set to retire. The article also details several other significant personnel changes across various financial institutions, including Crédit Agricole CIB, Triad Securities, BNY Mellon, OCC, Broadway Technology, and Canoe Intelligence.

articles.title: At U.S. Bank under Cecere, doing a giant deal takes 'discipline'
articles.summary: U.S. Bank CEO Andrew Cecere greenlit the company's largest deal in two decades: the $8 billion acquisition of MUFG Union Bank. Cecere emphasized a disciplined approach to mergers and acquisitions, stressing the importance of meaningful opportunities and aligning with U.S. Bank's growth strategy, particularly in the faster-growing West Coast market. The acquisition is expected to increase U.S. Bank's size by 20% and includes plans to integrate MUFG Union Bank's customer activity onto U.S. Bank's systems, despite initial IT risk management concerns.

articles.title: You Can Get Your Credit Score, but You May Have to Pay for It (Published 2021)
articles.summary: A new Consumer Reports analysis reveals that many popular credit apps may provide credit scores that differ from those used by lenders and often charge consumers for access to scores and reports. This highlights a significant drawback in the current credit system where individuals often have to pay to know their credit score, despite its importance for major financial decisions. Consumers are legally entitled to annual free credit reports, but not necessarily free credit scores.

articles.title: T. Rowe Price Releases Three New Fixed-Income ETFs
articles.summary: T. Rowe Price announced the launch of three new fixed-income exchange-traded funds (ETFs): the Total Return ETF (TOTR), the Ultra Short-Term Bond ETF (TBUX), and the QM U.S. Bond ETF (TAGG). These ETFs expand T. Rowe Price's total ETF offerings to eight, complementing its existing equity funds. The new funds are actively managed, reflecting the firm's long-standing strategic investing approach, and offer features like continuous daily trading and tax efficiency.
